      "name": "Absolute hemolysis index validation across five VAD operating points",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-pump-experimental-hemolysis-dataset",
      "description": "Hemolysis index (HI) predictions were generated by executing the calibrated CFD solver on a 14.2-million-element polyhedral mesh at five flow-speed combinations (3 L/min at 2400 RPM, 4 L/min at 2600 RPM, 5 L/min at 2800 RPM, 6 L/min at 3000 RPM, and 7 L/min at 3200 RPM). The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model was applied in post-processing to shear-stress and exposure-time fields extracted from converged steady-state solutions. Predicted HI values were compared against in-vitro measurements obtained from a modified ASTM F1841 loop protocol conducted at the FDA Division of Applied Mechanics laboratory (n=6 replicates per operating point). Normalised root-mean-square error across all five points was 8.3 %, with maximum point-wise deviation of 14.1 % at the 3 L/min condition, which is attributed to transitional flow effects not captured by the k-omega SST turbulence closure. Monte Carlo propagation of inlet boundary-condition uncertainty (±5 % flow rate, ±2 % rotational speed) yielded 95th-percentile HI predictions that remained below the 0.8 % absolute clinical threshold at all operating points. The validation team concluded that model fidelity is sufficient for regulatory submission at the stated operating envelope, with the caveat that the 3 L/min corner condition should be flagged for sensitivity review."
    },
